<TEXT>
retired rear adm oliver francis naquin 
commander of a sunken submarine whose rescue captured national 
attention 50 years ago died monday from an obstruction of the 
pancreas he was 85 
naquin commanded the submarine squalus which sank during a 
trial dive off the new hampshire coast in 1939 he and 32 sailors 
submarine were rescued by a diving bell that was lowered from the 
surface and attached to the hatch of the squalus 
another 26 men died when they were trapped in compartments that 
had flooded or been sealed off 
naquin died at malcolm grow medical center at andrews air force 
base in suburban maryland the washington post reported 
