<TEXT>
senators are preparing to decide an issue that 
touches some of americas most sensitive nerve endings should a 
member of a private club that bars women and minorities be 
confirmed as a federal judge 
the question is do organizations like the olympic club hurt 
people and it seems to me absolutely that they do professor 
stephen gillers of new york university school of law told the 
senate judiciary committee last week 
the question for the senate is whether to confirm san francisco 
attorney vaughn walker as a district court judge despite the fact 
that he has for 15 years belonged to that citys embattled olympic 
club long a bastion of white male dominance 
the club barred blacks from its rolls for decades and still 
refuses to admit women as full members 
the larger issue extending beyond california is whether the 
senate should confirm judges who belong to such clubs liberals and 
civil rights organizations say the answer is no 
the senate judiciary committee could take a step toward 
answering those questions thursday if it votes on whether to send 
the walker nomination to the senate floor supporters of walker are 
pushing for a vote 
judiciary committee chairman joseph r biden jr ddel hasnt 
announced whether he will call for a vote any one of walkers 
critics on the panel could block action under committee rules 
the walker nomination is the most pressing in the longrunning 
tugofwar between liberals and conservatives on the senate 
judiciary committee over federal judiciary nominees 
also facing the panel is a potentially more explosive dispute 
over president bushs naming of clarence thomas chairman of the 
equal employment opportunity commission as a judge of the us 
court of appeals in the district of columbia that issue is 
guaranteed to spill over into next year 
the lawmakers also are being asked to approve elevation of 
bushs cousin district judge john walker of new york to the 
appeals bench harvard law professor alan dershowitz alleges the 
nomination violates federal antinepotism law when the issue will 
be resolved is unclear 
thursdays executive session of the judiciary committee is the 
last planned for this year 
thus thursday could be the final trip to the plate in 1989 for 
vaughn walker in his frustrating twoyear quest for judicial 
confirmation 
sen howard m metzenbaum dohio an outspoken critic of 
discriminatory clubs and other liberals say such memberships 
create an image of unfairness that has no place on the bench the 
american bar association has adopted rules discouraging 
confirmation of judicial nominees who belong to clubs that bar 
minorities and women 
few if any senators defend discriminatory clubs but sen alan 
simpson rwyo and other conservatives say there are more 
important issues to consider in evaluating judicial nominees 
at first blush vaughn walkers credentials appear solid the 
silverhaired 45yearold attorney has a law degree from stanford 
a partnership in a bluechip company and a well qualified 
rating from his local bar association 
like most district court nominees he has the blessing of a 
homestate senator in this case republican pete wilson but his 
longtime membership in the olympic club has been dogging the 
nomination for almost two years 
the matter is made more complicated because after being besieged 
about the club and its discriminatory policy for eight months 
walker resigned in a letter dated feb 15 
but critics say thats not enough they say he was too slow in 
removing his name from the membership roles and did too little to 
fight the policy of excluding women 
i still wonder whether he resigned because he believed his 
club membership was wrong or because he sought to curry favor with 
the committee metzenbaum told a hearing thursday 
he questioned walker closely on why the resignation letter was 
not marked as received by the club until april 15 and why he paid 
his dues through march walker said he gave the letter to a club 
officer for delivery in february and that was the last he saw of 
it he said he inadvertently paid march dues because they were on 
the same bill with his february club expenses 
republican senators registered increasing impatience after 
listening to the interrogation simpson left for another hearing 
describing the questions as balderdash 
meanwhile the senate will debate monday and vote tuesday on 
rival republican and democratic proposals to provide economic aid 
to poland and hungary 
the democratic version authorizes a threeyear package with a 
value of nearly 1 billion while the republican version calls for 
a little more than half that the idea is to furnish funds to the 
two east european nations to assist them as they embark on 
wideranging reforms 
polish solidarity leader lech walesa will address a joint 
meeting of the house and senate at midweek 
the senate plans two days of action on bushs proposal to reduce 
the capital gains tax republicans who have been trying 
unsuccessfully to push the tax cut through congress all year are 
expected to be defeated and have promised that if they are they 
will not raise the issue again until 1990 
congressional leaders and bush administration officials continue 
their efforts to reach agreement on a package cutting 14 billion 
from this years deficit of 116 billion weeks of closeddoor 
bargaining has left democrats and republicans at odds over how to 
reduce the shortfall 
meanwhile 16 billion in cuts imposed under the grammrudman 
law on most federal programs oct 16 remain in effect 
</TEXT>
