<TEXT>
an agriculture department analysis shows total 
us grain production is so huge that yeartoyear changes in the 
pattern send tremors throughout the world 
when us crop production falters there is a good chance that 
global figures also will show a decline and when there are bumper 
us harvests particularly of feed grains the world stockpile is 
fatter 
last week the usda estimated this falls corn harvest the 
keystone of total us grain output at 759 billion bushels up 
54 percent from the droughtsavaged 1988 harvest 
put into international terms the us corn crop was 1928 
million metric tons allowing for about 2205 pounds per ton there 
are approximately 394 bushels of corn in each ton or 367 
bushels of wheat or soybeans 
a related supplyanddemand report showed total us grain 
production this year at more than 2838 million metric tons which 
includes corn output that is up sharply from 2041 million tons in 
1988 
the total includes wheat coarse grains such as corn sorghum 
oats and barley and milled rice it does not include us soybean 
production estimated at 527 million tons this year 
according to the analysis global production of grain in the 
198990 year a composite of dates for various crops is 
projected at about 1671 billion tons of which the us share of 
2838 million would represent about 17 percent 
last year when world grain output was 1559 billion tons the 
us share was 2041 million or 13 percent which reflected the 
drought reductions of 1988 
after totaling all production and deducting how much grain will 
be used in the year ahead the usda report said that by the end of 
the current season in 1990 the world will have about 2924 million 
tons of grain left over 
that would be down from 3087 million tons left in the global 
pantry this year and 4039 million tons remaining in inventories in 
1988 
of the total yearend grain stockpiles the united states is 
expected to have almost 74 million tons in 1990 or about 25 
percent of the world total 
this year with a global inventory of 3087 million tons of 
grain the united states accounted for 86 million tons or 28 
percent and in 1988 with a world inventory of 4039 million tons 
the us share was 1694 million tons 42 percent of the worlds 
total 
as the figures show the united states has borne the brunt of 
grain stockpile reduction while inventories in other countries 
have dropped only slightly 
this year for example the global reduction in yearend stocks 
from 1988 was about 952 million tons the united states accounted 
for 854 million tons of the yeartoyear decline 
if the 1990 projection holds true there will be a further 
global reduction of 163 million tons with the united states 
accounting for 12 million 
thus for the moment at least the major burden of holding 
surplus grain inventories has been shifted from the united states 
to other countries how that stacks up a year or two from now will 
depend on the weather and farmers reactions to market developments 
it will also depend on trade policies that affect exports and 
domestic consumption of grains in scores of countries that buy from 
american farmers or compete with them for export markets 
</TEXT>
