<TEXT>
leading soviet economists today began discussing a 
plan to increase wages and wholesale prices beginning next year 
and sell off some staterun enterprises to end an economic crisis 
and build a market system 
emphasizing the seriousness of the undertaking soviet president 
mikhail s gorbachev premier nikolai i ryzhkov and other members 
of the communist party politburo attended the session at moscows 
white marble hall of columns in the house of unions but they did 
not speak during the threeday conferences first session 
we cannot wait for reform economist leonid i abalkin 
chosen to head the push for economic reform said in his keynote 
speech the value of time has grown enormously 
the situation is dangerous the threat is grave added a 
second economist stanislav s shatalin 
the plan published last month in the economicheskaya gazeta 
newspaper offered a detailed analysis of an economy plagued by 
shortages hoarding a nearworthless currency topheavy 
bureaucracy and an increasing number of strikes 
in contrast to much of the public debate over the economy it 
provided a plan to free up prices jettison staterun enterprises 
that are losing money and aim toward convertibility of the ruble 
by the mid1990s 
the plan was a response to gorbachevs demand that economists 
stop their public bickering and formulate a plan of action 
ed hewett an american expert on the soviet economy told 
reporters watching a live broadcast of the session at the foreign 
ministry press center that if implemented there is a decent 
chance the plan will work 
but after more than four years of attempted reform that only 
have worsened the economy the public must be convinced and the 
government must chop away at the budget deficit and pentup 
consumer demand in the next year hewett said 
the next year is when were going to find out if theyre 
really going to do it he said abalkins thrown down the 
gauntlet 
abalkin deputy chairman of the council of ministers or 
cabinet told the conference of academics and economic managers 
they must overcome public disillusion 
in a poll conducted in conjunction with the economic proposal 
54 percent of those questioned said their first priority was 
introduction of strict discipline and order and 40 percent 
said they wanted the government to tighten not loosen price 
controls he said 
in response to another question 22 percent said the problems of 
the soviet economy are inherent in socialism abalkin said 
abalkins plan calls for wage increases beginning next year 
freefloating prices and healthy competition regulated by 
antimonopoly laws 
the plan proposes a timetable for conversion of the staterun 
economy to a mixture of stateheld industries publicly owned 
enterprises and private cooperatives 
the blueprint foresees the sale of shares in industrial 
enterprises establishment of a stock market competitive bidding 
for state contracts and legislative oversight to prevent abuses of 
the new system 
it also proposes temporary unemployment benefits for those who 
must be retrained when their jobs are eliminated 
sooner or later we are going to have to take the bitter 
medicine of raising prices said the report published in 
ekonomicheskaya gazetta without that it concludes there is no 
way to eliminate widespread shortages of food and consumer goods 
combat rampant speculation and the shadow economy in which 
scarse goods are being siphoned from legitimate channels and sold 
or traded under the table or on the black market 
gorbachev and other soviet leaders have been talking about the 
need for price reform for more than two years but lifting of state 
price controls has been put off indefinitely in the face of popular 
anxiety and instances of runaway inflation in yugoslavia and 
poland both of which have tried to establish more realistic 
pricing systems 
