<TEXT>
the supreme court today allowed states to ban 
doortodoor and telephone solicitation for prearranged funerals 
and burial 
the court without comment left intact a west virginia law 
challenged by a funeral service company as an infringement of 
freespeech rights 
the west virginia legislature in a 1983 law enacted extensive 
new regulations of the funeral service industry 
the law barred companies from making unsolicited sales pitches 
either doortodoor or over the phone to potential customers 
national funeral services inc sells prearranged or preneed 
funeral and burial services the company is a west virginia 
subsidiary of legacy one inc which owns funeral homes and 
cemeteries througout the southeast and midwest 
the company said it seeks to promote competition in the industry 
by offering its services before they are needed 
the 4th us circuit court of appeals last march said west 
virginias ban on doortodoor and telemarketing sales does not 
violate the freespeech protections of the constitutions first 
amendment 
the state has a legitimate interest in the protection of 
consumers from overreaching and highpressure sales tactics of this 
most unique product the 4th circuit court said west 
virginias ban on solicitation is supported by the substantial 
interest of protecting privacy 
the appeals court said the freespeech restrictions are minimal 
noting that the state permits directmail and newspaper 
advertisements for funeral services 
the supreme court on oct 2 left intact a similar virginia law 
prohibiting telephone solicitation for prearranged funerals 
the case acted on today is national funeral services vs 
rockefeller 89639 
