the supreme court today agreed to decide 
whether public school boards and school officials may be sued in 
state court not only in federal court for allegedly violating a 
students rights 
the justices said they will hear an appeal by a former florida 
high school student who says his rights were violated when an 
assistant principal broke into his car parked on school grounds in 
1986 
the student mark howlett later was suspended from st 
petersburg high school for five days for having alcoholic beverages 
in the car 
howlett and his mother elizabeth howlett accused the pinellas 
county school board and school officials of violating a federal 
civil rights law enacted in 1871 
a state appeals court dismissed the suit on grounds the state 
had not surrendered immunity for school boards and officials 
school officials and school boards as state agents enjoy 
broad but not absolute protection from federal lawsuits the 
supreme court has ruled that local governments and their officials 
may be sued under the 1871 law only if it can be proved the alleged 
violation of civil rights is part of an official policy 
the howlett case gives the high court an opportunity to set 
guidelines for such suits in state courts 
assistant principal thomas petit entered howletts locked 
volkswagen by pushing in a side window the car was blocking a 
construction site at the school and petit and others were tyring 
to move it 
once inside the car petit said he found three empty wine cooler 
bottles and another bottle containing alcoholic eggnog 
students are forbidden from taking alcohol onto school grounds 
howlett was criminally charged with illegal possession of alcohol 
on school property 
the charge was dismissed by a judge but howlett also was 
suspended from school for five days causing him automatically to 
get failing grades for part of a school term 
he later graduated from the high school and enrolled at st 
petersburg junior college 
a florida appeals court last feb 1 dismissed the civil rights 
suit filed by howlett and his mother 
the appeals court said the state has not waived its sovereign 
immunity from suits against it in its own state courts in such 
cases 
the state court said ground rules established by the supreme 
court are all distinguishable because they deal primarily with 
immunity in federal courts 
the case is howlett vs rose 895383 
