<TEXT>
scientists explaining the extent of 
damage caused by ships that recently ran aground on coral reefs in 
the florida keys can point to a reef hit by another ship five years 
ago that still bears obvious scars 
it can take 100 years for coral a hard shelter built up by 
millions of tiny animals to grow one yard 
we tend to think in human life spans but coral reef life 
spans are measured in the hundreds of years said alina szmant a 
coral reef specialist at the university of miami 
both humans and nature are putting pressure on the florida 
barrier reef a tract of about 6000 reefs extending from miami 
south along the florida keys to the dry tortugas west of key west 
this is the thirdlongest barrier reef in the world and its 
got more tourism than any other reef said lynn davidson marine 
habitat coordinator for greenpeace international we believe that 
the coral is acting a bit like a canary in a coal mine we know 
they are very fragile and they do respond very rapidly to stress 
the florida reefs are smaller than only australias great 
barrier reef and the caribbean reefs off belize 
new attention was drawn to the reefs by three ship groundings in 
less than a month 
on oct 25 the 155foot freighter alec owen matiland cut a 
200foot swath through a reef in the key largo national marine 
sanctuary five days later the 475foot phosphate hauler mavro 
vetranic scraped two to three acres of ocean bottom in the dry 
tortugas in the far western keys 
on saturday a 470foot cargo ship the elpis was refloated off 
a reef east of key largo after nearly 16 hours aground damage 
there was still being assessed 
in 1984 in the worst grounding of the decade the ship wellwood 
scarred 128000 square feet of coral on the marine sanctuarys 
molasses reef even though sponges are moving in and coral larvae 
are settling down the damage is still readily apparent said 
sanctuary biologist john halas 
there has not been very much new coral showing up in that 
area said ms szmant who studies coral reef physiology in the 
florida keys and caribbean 
but the human intrusion on the reefs home of 52 coral species 
and 10 times as many fish extends well beyond the damage caused 
by ships running aground 
other ways in which man can impact the reefs are anchor damage 
and divers kicking and breaking coral standing on the coral ms 
szmant said a lot of the boat traffic stirs up a lot of 
sediments which is bad for the coral weve seen a lot of damage 
done to the reef by just small boats 
coral needs clear water that ranges in temperature from 68 to 86 
degrees 
they are in a fragile location to begin with theyre on the 
northern edge of where coral grows said larry fooks assistant 
manager of john pennekamp coral reef state park which receives 
about 15 million visitors by boat each year theyre right at 
the point where if the temperature drops too much and all the 
conditions turn sour they could go too 
dredging for construction clouds the water fresh water runoff 
from the keys spoils the saline balance and sewage and possibly 
farm runoff from the florida mainland carry unwanted nutrients to 
the reefs in addition coral diseases that some scientists believe 
are caused or influenced by man also have appeared in the last 
three years 
a variety of measures have been proposed to protect the coral 
including quotas on visitors expanded sanctuaries and a shipping 
buffer zone 
we definitely need a good management plan to protect those 
reef resources said manley fuller president of the florida 
wildlife federation the 10000member state affiliate of the 
national wildlife federation 
its important for the public to be able to see experience 
and enjoy nature thats the future of conservation he said 
but we must guard against a situation of loving what we love to 
death and thats a real potential 
