<TEXT>
a judge with learning disabilities said monday 
more government funding is needed for juvenile criminals who have 
reading troubles 
if you cant read there are only two ways to earn a living 
welfare and crime judge jeffery gallet of new york said and 
the truth is crime pays more and has higher status in their 
communities 
gallet was a speaker at the first learning handicapped offender 
conference about 250 educators and corrections officials from 
around the country are attending the meeting which runs through 
wednesday 
james keeley conference chairman and a correction education 
specialist with the pennsylvania department of education said the 
gathering is needed to share successful programs and policies 
an estimated 20 percent to 40 percent of jailed juveniles and 
adults have learning disabilities said stephen j steurer 
executive director of the correctional education association in 
laurel md the disabilities include any difficulties with math or 
written language not caused by emotional or social malajustment in 
a person of average or better intelligence 
steurer said federal state and local governments have little 
interest in funding special education programs for convicts 
nobody wants to do anything with people who get in trouble with 
the law except lock them up he said 
gallet 47 a new york state family court judge said he has 
trouble spelling following a line of type distinguishing left 
from right and doing math in his head he was 32 when he found out 
learning disabilities were at the root of his struggles in school 
causing him to graduate last in his college class he now 
compensates by using an index card to read a calculator to add a 
watch to tell his right hand from his left and spellcheck computer 
software 
teenagers with learning disabilities often become frustrated 
and drop out of school gallet said 
we know what happens to the girls they become pregnant 
and what happens to the boys they turn to crime he said you 
dont have to know how to read to carry a pound of cocaine from the 
port authority in new york to virginia in a little knapsack 
by not paying the little bit now we pay forever gallet 
said we pay because they steal from us we pay because we have 
higher insurance rates we pay because we pay for their welfare we 
pay because we pay when they go into the adult criminal system 
gallet pointed to a program run by the bronx district attorneys 
office as a model for young offenders with learning disabilities 
under the program firsttime offenders 16 to 21 who are 
learning disabled can receive special education at the opportunity 
center which is run by the albert einstein college of medicine 
thomas olin director of the educational outreach program in the 
bronx district attorneys office said the 2yearold opportunity 
center appeared to lower the rate of rearrest of these offenders 
from 50 percent to 25 percent 
the bronx district attorneys office spends 400000 a year to 
serve 100 young offenders who qualify for the opportunity center 
olin said 
