<TEXT>
long known as an antiestablishment communist 
politician patiently awaiting his chance new east german premier 
hans modrow is a symbol of hope for wideranging political and 
economic reforms 
an engineer by trade and holder of a university economics 
degree the former communist party chief in dresden is expected to 
have much more clout as head of the cabinet than his colorless 
predecessor willi stoph 
the east german economy is a shambles says guenther buch a 
federal government researcher in berlin who watches east germany 
it will be the strategy of the party to allow a shift of power 
toward the council of ministers cabinet to lighten the burden of 
the economic disaster for the party he said the main 
responsibility in coming weeks will be with hans modrow 
analysts see modrow 61 as east germanys equivalent to soviet 
leader mikhail s gorbachev whose domestic program of greater 
openness and economic restructuring caught on among the east german 
public and was the main trigger of the convulsions sweeping the 
country in recent weeks 
many east germans as well as soviet officials made plain they 
would have preferred modrow in the post of east germanys top 
leader 
modrow has a reputation as a smart and modest communist who 
rejects hardline policies new communist party leader egon krenz 
remains associated with those policies despite ceding to pressure 
for change 
before the party announced his nomination as premier wednesday 
east berlins party bosses appeared intent to keep him at arms 
length in dresden where he became party secretary in 1973 
but he was never known to complain stayed true to his 
principles and became exceptionally popular in his district 115 
miles south of berlin 
in june central authorities singled him out for rare public 
criticism saying he failed to control bourgeois and enemy 
views in dresden after a large demonstration of citizens 
demanding free travel to the west 
married and the father of two children modrow began his party 
career as chief of the communist youth organization in east berlin 
in 195361 he won election to the central committee in 1967 and 
later held a propaganda post 
he was once considered a protege and possible successor of 
former leader erich honecker but the prerequisite a politburo 
post eluded him until last week 
like gorbachev modrow has made clear he thinks a policy of 
suppressing problems is counterproductive 
buch said the shape and speed of reform depends on the cabinet 
modrow names and on how much power the reformers will have on a 
revamped central committee expected to emerge from an extraordinary 
meeting next month 
for now modrows appointment seems to be a signal from the 
politburo aimed at pacifying the broad masses buch said we 
must await the personnel and economic decisions in the next few 
days 
</TEXT>
