<TEXT>
hundreds of university of massachusetts 
students put down their books and picked up placards monday to 
boycott classes in a protest of state budget cuts that are forcing 
fee increases 
the state of massachusetts must not be allowed to let the 
younger generation pay for the mistakes of the present 
generation said lisa nelson a junior from sunderland and a 
boycott organizer 
the mood on campus was festive as picket lines snaked around 
buildings and people carrying banners marched through the student 
union nearly 2000 of the campus 25000 students gathered on the 
steps of the student center to hear speakers at an afternoon rally 
calling for raising taxes not cutting education 
you need to convince your representatives and senators that 
you are a force to be reckoned with that you will support them if 
they support you said history professor bruce laurie vice 
president of the faculty union 
organizers said the length of the protest depended on enthusiasm 
and participation by students at the universitys boston campus and 
at other state schools 
the boycott protested a 25 million cut in public higher 
education brought on by massachusetts fiscal crisis the amherst 
campus share of the cutback is 64 million and follows a 5 
percent slash ordered in july said paul j page vice chancellor 
for finance and administration 
laurie said an informal census among his colleagues indicated 60 
percent of mondays classes were canceled because of the boycott 
university spokesmen said they were still trying to determine the 
extent of the boycott by early afternoon but some classes were 
being held 
chancellor joseph duffey who was out of town monday said 
earlier that the administration would not endorse a student strike 
although he was sympathetic to their feelings 
deirdre ling vice chancellor for university relations and 
development said it was too soon to say if action would be taken 
against striking students 
at thompson hall where four auditoriums normally are packed 
with 200 and 300 students only about two dozen students sat in 
each room said john cole president of the faculty union 
the union was not actively involved in the strike but it had 
sent the students a letter of support 
on thursday university trustees authorized boosting a special 
student curriculum fee by up to 350 next semester in response to 
the proposed cuts 
the boost would raise the 165 fee at the amherst campus to 515 
and bring the universitys total mandatory fees to 1465 tuition 
which was raised 8 percent this fall is 1512 
theyre raising the cost so much that theyre cutting out the 
poor people said jim pak a junior from fairfax va 
</TEXT>
