<TEXT>
the federal fund that pays for the nations 
presidential campaigns is still suffering from declining income 
threatening public financing of the quadrennial battle for the 
white house the chairman of the federal election commission says 
fec chairman danny lee mcdonald wrote members of congress 
earlier this month to say that fewer and fewer americans are 
checking the box on their tax returns to send 1 to the campaign 
fund 
through august of this year mcdonald said only 311 million 
had been deposited in the fund from checkoffs on 1988 tax returns 
if the trend holds he said the fund will receive less this year 
than the 33 million pumped in last year 
the balance of the fund has shrunk dramatically due to the 
inflationary pressures on the payouts to candidates mcdonald 
said in his letter if the trend continues by the end of the 
1996 presidential campaign the balance will be in a negative 
position 
the payments to presidential campaigns are increased by 
inflation in each election cycle whether or not the funds income 
has increased the fec pointed out this trend to congress earlier 
this year and asked congress to look for ways to remedy the 
situation 
the money from the checkoff is used to match individual 
contributions to presidential candidates primary campaigns and to 
pay the entire cost of the general election presidential race for 
the two major party candidates 
primary candidates who raise a certain minimum amount of money 
can apply for federal funds to match dollarfordollar the amounts 
of individual contributions of 250 or less since overall primary 
spending is capped there is also a limit to the amount that can be 
matched 
in the general elections major party candidates can accept no 
private contributions and must rely completely on federal funds 
</TEXT>
