<TEXT>
students hoping to impress wouldbe bosses 
with their straight a grades would be helped along under an 
ambitious new plan to use computers to link young jobseekers with 
potential employers 
it is called the incentive to learn project and its backers are 
no less than american businesses eager to get qualified workers 
with basic skills and a good track record 
the need for this is to set up a framework whereby employers 
and workbound students can communicate more effectively said 
barry rogstead president of the american business conference 
abc together with the national alliance of business and 
educational testing service plans to set up a computerized 
information system that will record a students achievements and 
make the record available to potential employers 
they call it a training and experience information system 
beginning in the sixth or seventh grade rogstead said the 
student works on building a file which contains that students 
employment history any summer jobs course transcripts evaluation 
and some testing it will be much more a performance assessment 
than just simple percentile rankings on an achievement test 
rogstead said the idea will be tested in five to 25 labor 
markets in the next two to three years 
it will be an opportunity for students who never before were 
able to get into an employer network to get into the game in an 
organized way he said there is no question that the business 
community will have to channel in some seed money 
the idea was broached at the national governors conference last 
july by the american business conference 
companies are the largest customers of what the school 
supplies educated graduates said a statement issued by the abc 
in the past companies were fairly indifferent shoppers that 
must change the workforce is shrinking at just the time that 
demand for literate and arithmetically adept employees is 
expanding firms have no choice but to demand greater quality from 
the schools 
rogstead said a problem of the past has been that business has 
not articulated well what it requires from students and that at 
those times when information was asked from schools it was not 
always forthcoming 
there is a lack of communication from both sides he said 
asking rhetorically are we giving the student a very concrete 
sense that if he attempts to do better in school and take tougher 
courses anybody out there in the business world is going to take 
time to notice 
can we ask why students are not motivated if we dont 
differentiate one high school diploma from another 
the information system will be called worklink 
a brochure says that students would compile their records at 
their own pace and these records would be readily accessed by 
employers the student could order a copy of his or her record to 
be sent to specific employers agencies or training institutions 
the individual would control his or her worklink record only 
attainment not failure would be recorded the brochure sys 
worklink records begun in high school could serve persons 
throughout their working careers with continued updates at a number 
of agencies in the community a persons worklink record would 
eventually be usable throughout the us 
