<TEXT>
chop em burn em or plow them under but 
get rid of them before the next westerly wind starts to blow mayor 
darrell bender wants federal help with his tumbleweed problem 
theres weeds out there over my head and im six feet tall 
the mayor said monday after meeting with officials of the us army 
corps of engineers from pierre 
ballshaped weeds grew to the size of cars on the wide mud flats 
created by the falling level of the missouri river the water line 
is 38 feet below the full mark 
last week strong winds snapped them loose and sent them bouncing 
into mobridge by the thousands where the weeds buried homes 
clogged streets and snagged in treetops 
the big concern is fire said bender because tumbleweeds burn 
explosively 
the city spent 8500 gathering and destroying the weeds most 
of that borrowed from the snow removal budget our city is 4180 
people and that cuts a dent in our budgeting process bender 
said 
corps officials told bender to send a letter detailing his costs 
and asking for reimbursement but made no promises 
theres no money allocated to pay for the cleanup or to destroy 
the millions of tumbleweeds still on federal land the officials 
said the weeds are growing thick in an area about 2 miles long and 
up to a mile wide bender said 
corps officials toured the tumbleweed areas monday to get ideas 
for control they gave no timetable and said they dont know 
whether the weeds will be chopped up burned or plowed under 
the corps officials said the government plans to seed the mud 
flats with a crop that will deter tumbleweeds next summer 
