<TEXT>
a coalition of centerright parties led by 
novelist mario vargas llosa swept mayoral races nationwide 
according to results released monday strengthening vargas llosas 
bid for the presidency 
despite death threats from maoist shining path guerrillas 
peruvians turned out in large numbers sunday to elect mayors in 
nearly 2000 municipalities 
guerrillas caused the most problems in huancayo an andean city 
140 miles east of lima election officials there counted ballots by 
candlelight sunday night after the shining path blew up several 
power pylons causing a blackout 
vargas llosas democratic front won 23 mayoral posts of limas 
40 suburban districts 
the united left a coalition of marxistled parties won five of 
the posts the socialist accord a grouping of moderate left 
parties won one district mayors seat and an independent emerged 
victorious in another results for the remaining seats were not in 
a political independent television personality ricardo belmont 
defeated juan inchaustegui vargas llosas candidate in the race 
for mayor of metropolitan lima 
but belmont said before sundays voting that he supports vargas 
llosa in the april presidential race and the novelist embraced 
belmont as one of his own 
the governing aprista party of president alan garcia lost all 18 
of the posts it held in the lima districts 
with peru suffering from 3000 percent annual inflation the 
aprista party was given little chance of winning many seats 
the democratic front also dominated races in major cities 
throughout peru according to vote tallies available monday 
with counting completed in 15 of perus 24 state capitals the 
democratic front controlled eight of the mayoral offices the 
united left two the aprista party two and political independents 
or small regional parties held the others 
this has been the best demonstration before the world that 
peru is not the shining path is not crimes or kidnappings but is 
a country that wants to live in peace and democracy vargas llosa 
said 
results from small towns throughout peru were not expected for 
several days because of poor communications analysts said they 
expected them to follow the pattern of the bigger cities 
the shining path which has been fighting since 1980 to topple 
perus elected governments sought to disrupt the voting as the 
first stage in its campaign to block the presidential election 
death threats by the rebels who have killed scores of officials 
and candidates this year frightened anyone from running for office 
in more than 80 municipalities 
voting was mandatory but the rebels threatened to kill anyone 
who cast ballots the armed forces and police took control of 
larger towns and cities and provided security for voters 
total voter turnout was not known because of the lack of 
communication with remote regions 
despite precautions rebel violence killed seven people on 
election day 
authorities said shining path guerrillas shot and killed the 
aprista partys mayoral candidate early sunday in azangaro near 
the bolivian border 470 miles southeast of lima 
a man and a woman were electrocuted by falling power lines when 
a pylon was dynamited in the andean town of concepcion 
three adults and a child were killed and three people were 
wounded when one of them stepped on a mine on a road a few miles 
north of huancayo as they were returning home from the polls 
police said 
