<TEXT>
the general assemblys budget committee on 
monday decided to continue funding a 94 million conference center 
in ethiopia and a 44 million center in thailand despite western 
opposition 
we continue to have strong reservations concerning these two 
construction projects said lawrence grossman the us delegate 
on the budget committee he said the money should have been put 
to better use 
the ethiopian center in addis ababa has been especially 
criticized by the western nations that have been the main source of 
famine relief for ethiopia which has suffered recurring droughts 
and is fighting two rebel movements 
but the united states britain and other western nations that 
said the conference facilities were unnecessary joined in the 
consensus to approve more funds toward their construction 
there have been efforts to suspend or cut funds for the two 
projects since they were first proposed in 1984 third world 
countries that have a majority in the general assembly and budget 
committee have managed to overrule western objections 
on monday the budget committee approved 273 million over the 
next two years for the addis ababa center with the basic 
construction to be completed in 1993 
it allocated 168 million for the next two years on the bangkok 
center main construction is to be finished by the end of 1991 
the developing nations say the united nations has established 
facilities in new york paris vienna washington rome and geneva 
and they deserve more representation in the un system 
