<TEXT>
an evenly divided supreme court cleared the 
way monday for the partial merger of detroits two daily newspapers 
in its first ruling on a 1970 law aimed at saving failing 
newspapers 
but opponents of the deal said the 44 vote suggests such joint 
operating agreements are on shaky ground they vowed to fight to 
restrain future mergers in any of the remaining two dozen or so 
cities with competing dailies 
the high court split affirmed a lower court ruling that former 
attorney general edwin meese iii acted reasonably last year when he 
approved plans by the detroit free press and the detroit news to 
merge their business production and advertising staffs but 
maintain editorial independence 
the federal newspaper preservation act of 1970 authorizes the 
attorney general to give financially failing newspapers an 
exemption from federal antitrust laws 
justice byron r white removed himself from the case for 
unexplained personal reasons the remaining eight justices 
announced their ruling in a terse statement that did not reveal how 
each voted 
the future of such newspaper mergers is really on eggshells 
said a leading opponent of the detroit agreement w edward 
wendover publisher and editor of the community crier of plymouth 
in suburban detroit 
so i think the focus of our opposition now switches to 
capitol hill he said 
supporters of the detroit agreement said the papers will remain 
editorially if not financially competitive 
were joined at the wallet but not at the heart said free 
press reporter joe swickard 
were very happy that the last hurdle has finally been 
crossed said sheila gibbons a spokeswoman for gannett co inc 
owner of the detroit news with the history of the two 
newspapers im sure you will continue to see heavy competition 
people are happy glad its over said robert j hall 
publisher and chairman of the free press but weve been through 
this before and there is probably still some degree of hesitation 
and disbelief 
the combination will become effective nov 27 with the first 
joint saturday paper on dec 2 and the first joint sunday paper the 
following day said william keating president of the joint 
operating entity the detroit newspaper agency 
under a 100year agreement the detroit newspapers will combine 
their business advertising and production departments but maintain 
separate editorial staffs 
the news will receive 55 percent of the merged companys profits 
during the first year dropping to 50 percent by the seventh year 
and thereafter 
the 44 vote by the justices leaves in doubt how the court would 
treat future newspaper agreements with white presumably the 
controlling vote 
gannett is the nations largest newspaper publishing group 
knightridder inc owner of the free press is the second largest 
they proposed the partial merger in 1986 
opponents of the deal calling themselves michigan citizens for 
an independent press contend that the free press is not a failing 
newspaper even though it lost 10 million a year between 1981 and 
1986 
the opponents say the free press and the news which lost 50 
million in the same period were unprofitable solely because both 
papers cut prices in an unsuccessful effort to force each other out 
of business 
knightridders lawyers had said the free press would be shut 
down if the joint operating agreement did not go through but an 
investor group from michigan recently offered to buy the newspaper 
for 68 million 
the newspapers have said that the agreement will eliminate some 
500 jobs they said closing the free press would have eliminated 
2200 jobs 
the justices were urged by the bush administration to uphold the 
partial merger to protect the dwindling number of twonewspaper 
cities in the united states 
but opponents of the deal said such a ruling would be a 
terrific incentive for monopoly conduct by competing papers 
giving them a blueprint on how to force approval of a joint 
operating agreement 
a federal appeals court panel here last year voted 21 to uphold 
meeses decision the full appeals court split 54 in refusing to 
review the threejudge panels rulings 
</TEXT>
