the senate reached bipartisan compromise 
monday on a 738 million aid plan for poland and hungary two days 
before solidarity leader lech walesa is to address a joint meeting 
of congress 
the compromise ends a long and divisive battle over the proper 
scale of aid to poland and incorporates safeguards sought by 
republicans to make sure the money doesnt go to communist 
governments 
senate democrats originally had sought a threeyear spending 
level for the two east european nations of 989 millions while 
republicans sought a 585 million authorization level 
the agreement is expected to pass the senate on tuesday and 
must be reconciled with a slightly different house version 
the heart of the compromise aid bill the establishment of an 
enterprise fund to help both countries establish freemarket 
systems allocates 260 million for poland and 65 million for 
hungary overall the bill recognizing polands serious economic 
problems would give that country 657 million over the threeyear 
period while hungary would receive 81 million 
earlier senate majority leader george mitchell urged president 
bush to go to berlin to hail the figurative and literal 
destruction of the berlin wall 
to acknowledge the tremendous significance of the symbolic 
destruction of the berlin wall and to give voice to the 
exhilaration felt by all americans i urge president bush to travel 
to west berlin mitchell said 
earlier monday presidential spokesman marlin fitzwater said he 
could not foresee any set of circumstances at this moment that 
would induce bush to go to berlin 
in related action the senate unanimously approved a resolution 
welcoming the opening of the wall condemning it as a symbol of 
oppression and calling for its complete destruction 
mitchell said the president should react to events in east 
germany by quickly convening a meeting of the western allies to 
plan a unified and coordinated response to the tumultuous spin of 
events in eastern europe and its implications for the future 
the maine democrat urged bush to promptly suspend trade barriers 
against the soviet union and to reward soviet president mikhail s 
gorbachevs reform program by granting moscow observer status at 
international economic institutions 
the wall symbol of division between east and west has been 
dissolved by the east german peoples desire for change for 
freedom for control of their future mitchell said 
it has been 40 years since the west demonstrated its 
commitment to the citys freedom by helping break the blockade 
strangling berlin he said it would be fitting for the 
american president to travel there to underscore the american 
commitment to the freedom of berlin and our support for democratic 
reform in east germany 
mitchell also urged the president to give more urgency than ever 
to completing the talks underway in vienna on reductions in 
conventional forces 
he said success in the vienna talks can complement the reforms 
taking place in the east 
meanwhile house democratic leader richard a gephardt sharply 
scored bushs reaction to events in eastern europe saying even 
as the walls of the modern jericho come tumbling down we have a 
president who is inadequate to the moment 
