<TEXT>
advocates for the elderly are dismayed that 
president bush has not called what would be the fourth decennial 
white house conference on aging for 1991 to help guide a graying 
america into the next century 
time is short for planning a productive conference that can 
steer clear of intergenerational conflicts and avoid political 
pitfalls that plagued the last such gathering in 1981 supporters 
say opinion is divided however on whether the inaction is a 
result of normal bureaucratic delay a reluctance to convene a 
populist gathering of the elderly or a desire to limit its scope 
there is a growing sense that the white house really doesnt 
want this conference and therefore would like to delay it as long 
as possible said fernando torrezgil presidentelect of the 
american society on aging 
the white house conferences which bring together thousands of 
delegates from around the nation to focus on the needs and 
contributions of the elderly and their role in society have been a 
decennial tradition since 1961 
the first two helped launch federal programs ranging from 
medicare to mealsonwheels the 1981 gathering though marred by 
politics helped fend off cuts in social security 
congress in 1987 passed legislation authorizing not requiring 
the president to continue the tradition in 1991 but bush has yet 
to announce his intentions he is interested in having one but 
more work needs to be done before a final decision can be made 
said white house spokeswoman alixe glen 
twentyfour major groups the leadership council of aging 
organizations wrote to bush in august urging him to call a 
conference and 90 house members sent a similar request in 
september warning that time is running out the house letter 
was initiated by rep thomas downey dny who said previous 
presidents acted earlier to call each of the preceding conferences 
expectations that a 1991 conference was a certainty now are 
giving way to skepticism about whether there will be one said 
dan quirk executive director of the national association of state 
units on aging 
advocates say the 1991 conference is needed to help the nation 
prepare for its unprecedented aging the population 65 and over is 
expected to rise from 12 percent in 1987 to nearly 23 percent by 
2040 in sheer numbers that means an increase from 298 million in 
1987 to 681 million in 2040 with the biggest increases occuring 
among the oldest of the elderly 
every institution in society is going to have to respond to 
the needs of a much older population quirk said this 
conference could set the stage to prepare for that demographic 
revolution 
torrezgil predicted bush eventually would yield to pressure 
but that the conference date would be pushed back from 1991 
bush could derive real dividends from convening a bipartisan 
conference that is a genuine town meeting on issues in the field 
of aging said arthur flemming a former health education and 
welfare secretary who chaired the 1971 conference and was deputy 
chairman 10 years later 
but daniel schulder of the national council on the aging said 
bush may be dragging his feet to limit a conferences scope and 
reduce grassroots interest generated by the state and local forums 
that typically precede it 
if you delay long enough you only have time for a much 
smaller kind of conference directed toward mavens and experts 
rather than a popular conference he said the signals are 
clearly dilatory 
the death earlier this year of rep claude pepper of florida 
the singular champion of the elderly has limited congress ability 
to exert pressure for a 1991 conference schulder said 
in the absence of a decision from washington some states are 
moving ahead on their own illinois for example is organizing 
local forums and a state conference regardless of what bush does 
the challenge to be part of the solution to the everincreasing 
problems of an aging society is an opportunity we do not want to 
see forsaken said state aging director janet otwell 
while most advocacy groups are pressing for a 1991 conference a 
few voices question its usefulness and warn of a potential backlash 
against the elderly 
dr robert butler a former director of the national institute 
on aging questions whether spending millions on a vapid 
decennial ritual that he said could fuel conflicts between the 
young and old while accomplishing little 
let us not provide another opportunity for writers press and 
the public to image older people as special pleaders or greedy 
geezers butler wrote recently he said an annual report on the 
status of the aged would be better 
one advocacy group avoiding the push for the white house 
conference is the gray panthers which believes many concerns of 
the elderly such as health care and housing are better addressed 
as issues for society overall we feel that we need to take a 
more holistic look at the problems of our society said executive 
director frances humphreys we would love to see an 
intergenerational conference 
supporters of a conference on aging believe it must focus not on 
what government can do for senior citizens but on how the nations 
aging affects all of society and on concerns that cut across 
generations 
joyce berry acting us commissioner on aging this summer told 
a house panel that health and human services secretary louis 
sullivan was interested in focusing the conference on a binding 
of generations and capitalizing upon what generations can do for 
each other 
issues such as access to health care nursing home costs 
employment income security and family caregiving are no longer 
older persons issues they are family issues said illinois 
otwell 
the national council on the aging suggested a concurrent white 
house conference on children so common problems could be evaluated 
in a coordinated way without pitting young and old against one 
another 
dual conferences could help blunt the resentment of people who 
like to think in terms of generational warfare schulder said 
conference supporters say that besides promoting generational 
unity the meeting must avoid the politicization of 1981 when the 
reagan administration was accused of trying to pack the event with 
supporters of proposed budget cuts in social security and other 
programs the legislation that authorizes the 1991 conference says 
delegates shall be selected without regard to political 
affiliation or past partisan activity 
were hoping for a conference in 1991 but only if its 
constructive and only if its properly funded and meaningful 
said john rother legislative director of the american association 
of retired persons i dont think anybody wants a repeat of 
1981 
</TEXT>
