<TEXT>
here at a glance are highlights of actions 
taken monday by the supreme court 
 
newspapers 
 
an evenly divided court upheld the planned partial merger of 
detroits two daily newspapers 
the justices by a 44 vote affirmed a ruling that former 
attorney general edwin meese iii acted reasonably last year when he 
approved a joint operating agreement for the two papers the 
detroit free press and the detroit news 
the federal newspaper preservation act of 1970 authorizes the 
attorney general to give financially failing newspapers an 
exemption from federal antitrust laws todays ruling was the 
courts first on a joint operating agreement between newspapers 
the partial merger had been challenged by a group of michigan 
advertisers and readers 
todays 44 split which under the high courts rules 
automatically upheld a federal appeals courts decision was set up 
when justice byron r white disqualified himself from the case for 
unexplained personal reasons 
a 44 vote by the justices sets no binding precedent for similar 
controversies in the future mainly because there is no clue as to 
the reasoning of any justice 
the case is michigan citizens for an independent press vs 
thornburgh 881640 
 
drug testing 
 
the court permitted random drug testing of boston police 
officers providing new evidence the justices are willing to allow 
widespread testing of government employees in jobs affecting public 
safety 
the court without comment left intact a ruling that forcing 
police officers to undergo the tests even when there is no reason 
to suspect drug abuse does not violate their privacy rights 
the case is guiney vs roache 89205 
 
funerals 
 
the court allowed states to ban doortodoor and telephone 
solicitation for prearranged funerals and burial 
the court without comment left intact a west virginia law 
challenged by a funeral service company as an infringement of 
freespeech rights 
the case is national funeral services vs rockefeller 89639 
 
tax debts 
 
the court agreed to consider making it easier to collect all 
federal taxes owed by bankrupt corporations 
at issue are government attempts to hold officials of bankrupt 
corporations personally responsible for paying the owed taxes 
the case is us vs energy resources 89255 
 
river rafting 
 
the court allowed arizona to tax the river raft trips a salt 
lake city business runs through grand canyon national park in 
arizona 
the justices without comment turned away arguments that the 
tax is unconstitutional 
the case is moki mac river expeditions vs arizona department of 
revenue 89405 
