<TEXT>
detroit free press executive editor heath 
meriwether walked out into his newsroom monday and saw a sea of 
smiling faces 
meriwether told the 70 or so employees what they already knew 
but were waiting to hear from him the us supreme court by a 44 
tie had cleared the way for the free press and the detroit news to 
partially merge their operations 
whoever said a tie was like kissing your sister didnt have it 
quite right meriwether said 
since 1986 knightridder inc owner of the free press and 
gannett co inc owner of the news had been seeking to merge 
their business circulation and advertising departments editorial 
departments would remain separate 
were joined at the wallet but not at the heart said joe 
swickard a free press court reporter 
the joint operating agreement or joa will begin on nov 27 
and the first joint issue will come out dec 2 said william 
keating president of the detroit newspaper agency which will 
handle the newspapers combined operations the newspaper will 
publish joint issues on saturdays and sundays 
this guarantees that there will be two editorial voices in the 
detroit community for a long time 100 years according to the 
terms of the contract keating said 
the tie vote by the nations highest court meant that earlier 
court decisions upholding the joint operating agreement would 
stand justice byron r white had excused himself from the case for 
undisclosed personal reasons 
the michigan citizens for an independent press an organization 
which challenged the arrangement will not ask the court for a 
