<TEXT>
european finance ministers on monday 
listened sympathetically to britains alternative approach for 
closer european monetary ties but did not wholeheartedly endorse 
it according to a british official 
john major britains chancellor of the exchequer told a news 
conference that the plan would be discussed next month at a summit 
in strasbourg france of the leaders of the 12nation european 
community 
there is no doubt in my mind that the british paper was taken 
very seriously by the delegations he said 
he acknowledged that it wasnt universally applauded there 
were mixed views about it but it had a good deal of support 
major attending his first ec meeting as britains top treasury 
official replaced nigel lawson who quit last month in a policy 
dispute with prime minister margaret thatcher lawsons resignation 
rocked the british government 
other european finance officials have expressed concern that the 
british approach could slow the movement toward full economic and 
monetary union of the dozen nations of the trading bloc also 
called the common market 
earlier this month the british government unveiled what it 
described as its marketbased approach to the development of 
closer monetary ties it calls for removing restrictions so that 
all the european currencies would be legal tender acceptable for 
savings and transactions throughout the community 
the british have offered their plan as an alternative to 
sweeping proposals that would lead to a common currency and central 
bank system the recommendations were laid out in a report drawn up 
last spring by a panel of european central bankers the committee 
was led by jacques delors president of the european commission 
the communitys executive body 
the delors plan sets out three stages for implementing monetary 
union leaders of the ec nations agreed at a summit last june in 
madrid to go ahead with the first stage generally calling for 
closer economic and monetary ties 
at mondays meeting the finance ministers gave a green light to 
proposals setting the framework for closer consultations among the 
nations on economic and monetary matters that framework would be 
part of the first phase of the monetary plan which is scheduled to 
begin july 1 
as part the first phase all currencies would be linked in the 
exchange rate mechanism of the european monetary system which 
keeps their values roughly steady within certain bands the 
currencies of britain greece and portugal remain outside the 
linkage 
mrs thatcher who has long resisted entering the pound into the 
system agreed at the madrid summit to do so but only under certain 
conditions she gave no timetable 
major reiterated britains objections to the later stages of the 
delors report i made it clear that the united kingdom has 
very considerable worries about stages two and three he said 
mrs thatcher has argued that the radical moves to a joint 
currency and central bank system would force nations to give up 
some of their sovereignty to new institutions 
the move toward monetary union would enlarge on the communitys 
push to create a single market in late 1992 by lifting the barriers 
that bar the free movement of people money goods and services 
