for wolf to put together a managementlabor team to buy out the 
company said analyst louis marckesano of janney montgomery scott 
inc in philadelphia 
failing that he could put together a restructuring similar to 
what happened with allegis 
allegis corp the former parent of united was broken up in 
1987 after coniston obtained a 14 percent stake in the company and 
demanded an end to its diversification within the travel industry 
in response to the pressure allegis sold its westin and hilton 
international hotel operations and its hertz car rental business 
marckesano said there are difficulties associated with a 
recapitalization because ual has few assets to sell to raise cash 
he noted that ual has cash on hand and could sell its aircraft 
and lease them back 
the best alternative is a managementlabor buyout 
marckesano said 
officials of the air line pilots association chapter at united 
met last week with coniston principals and financier saul 
steinberg a friend of wolf who is seeking government permission to 
buy more than 15 percent of ual 
pilots said they have discussed a revised bid with ual 
management but they hinted last week that they might resume a work 
slowdown in effect earlier this year unless the ual board recommits 
in the next two weeks to majority employee ownership 
uniteds machinists who opposed the failed buyout bid also met 
last week with coniston principals 
they say they wont support any highly leveraged deal that could 
threaten the airlines viability or that would involve wolf 
